{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-chapter-level-2-chapter-level-2-tsx","path":"/topics/halitosis/background-information/definition/","result":{"pageContext":{"chapter":{"id":"87fc1b54-fd2b-549d-b5e8-0753c521ebf9","slug":"definition","fullItemName":"Definition","depth":2,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field 068a8405-f6be-4cf6-93aa-0766f89f1986 --><h2>What is it?</h2><!-- end field 068a8405-f6be-4cf6-93aa-0766f89f1986 -->","summary":"","htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item 6db88106-3baf-4b5e-9a87-d170f4ded3fa --><!-- begin field f7ca683f-8d79-4cac-a61d-ee910debd201 --><ul><li><strong>Halitosis ('bad breath' or 'oral malodour') is a general term used to describe an unpleasant or offensive odour in the breath </strong>[<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/halitosis/references/\">Porter and Scully, 2006</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/halitosis/references/\">Mokeem, 2014</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/halitosis/references/\">Seemann et al, 2014</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/halitosis/references/\">Silva, 2018</a>]<strong>, or malodour beyond a socially acceptable level </strong>[<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/halitosis/references/\">Aydin, 2014</a>]<strong>, regardless of the underlying cause. It can be classified as:</strong><ul><li><strong>Physiological.</strong><ul><li>This is usually transient and normal, for example, following a nights sleep ('morning breath') or fasting.</li><li>Non-pathological halitosis may also be lifestyle-related, for example caused by smoking or ingesting certain odiferous foods or drinks.</li></ul></li><li><strong>Pathological.</strong><ul><li>Intra-oral halitosis — the odour originates from a problem within the mouth (common).</li><li>Extra-oral halitosis — the odour originates from a non-oral disease (uncommon).</li></ul></li><li><strong>Psychogenic or subjective</strong> (the person believes that they have halitosis when it is not objectively perceived or confirmed by others).<ul><li>Pseudo-halitosis — the person eventually accepts that they do not have halitosis with reassurance, explanation, and self-care advice.</li><li>Halitophobia — the person has a persistent fear of having halitosis despite reassurance, explanation, and treatment. They may become fixated with teeth and tongue cleaning, and may change their behaviour (such as covering their mouth when talking and avoiding people), to try and minimize perceived symptoms. In addition, they may misintepret other people's behaviour (such as opening windows, sniffing, touching the nose) as evidence of their halitosis.</li></ul></li></ul></li></ul><p>[<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/halitosis/references/\">Porter and Scully, 2006</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/halitosis/references/\">Bollen and Beikler, 2012</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/halitosis/references/\">Scully and Greenman, 2012</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/halitosis/references/\">Aydin, 2014</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/halitosis/references/\">Mokeem, 2014</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/halitosis/references/\">Seemann et al, 2014</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/halitosis/references/\">Singh, 2015</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/halitosis/references/\">Kapoor, 2016</a>]</p><!-- end field f7ca683f-8d79-4cac-a61d-ee910debd201 --><!-- end item 6db88106-3baf-4b5e-9a87-d170f4ded3fa -->","topic":{"id":"ea95b9d4-34a7-5d1a-82a8-55bfdd82196e","topicId":"fe0b6e92-2668-4612-aca4-2a9b60ac4f39","topicName":"Halitosis","slug":"halitosis","lastRevised":"Last revised in September 2019","chapters":[{"id":"fbb800d8-0a88-595c-b899-0a65190b8e58","fullItemName":"Summary","slug":"summary","subChapters":[]},{"id":"fd2b97bd-db6b-55cc-b4e2-35124cffec66","fullItemName":"Have I got the right topic?","slug":"have-i-got-the-right-topic","subChapters":[]},{"id":"6bd01b8c-56bc-586d-aff5-f44fdb32ee60","fullItemName":"How up-to-date is this topic?","slug":"how-up-to-date-is-this-topic","subChapters":[{"id":"78fa51ef-a4b8-5018-b7e3-42049eace7f4","slug":"changes","fullItemName":"Changes"},{"id":"5cdbf49b-e67d-54e2-b879-dcd54d37cb53","slug":"update","fullItemName":"Update"}]},{"id":"81ff3380-c70b-5c69-9e8a-461ac2bc4554","fullItemName":"Goals and outcome measures","slug":"goals-outcome-measures","subChapters":[{"id":"b414cfd5-0732-59ba-ba20-d7d239b332c4","slug":"goals","fullItemName":"Goals"},{"id":"e512b3a8-808c-5329-8940-83d75972d158","slug":"outcome-measures","fullItemName":"Outcome measures"},{"id":"604b5628-660e-569a-8f50-d379558771c4","slug":"audit-criteria","fullItemName":"Audit criteria"},{"id":"3a6a6d00-0dc3-5860-a276-34731a999af7","slug":"qof-indicators","fullItemName":"QOF indicators"},{"id":"9ee9cb7a-0992-524e-98fb-616b92d893f2","slug":"qipp-options-for-local-implementation","fullItemName":"QIPP - Options for local implementation"},{"id":"f38e08d7-1583-5058-ab24-a47bd4d4bbbc","slug":"nice-quality-standards","fullItemName":"NICE quality standards"}]},{"id":"e87cff44-451c-59da-b2c8-3358cd4ad931","fullItemName":"Background information","slug":"background-information","subChapters":[{"id":"87fc1b54-fd2b-549d-b5e8-0753c521ebf9","slug":"definition","fullItemName":"Definition"},{"id":"e7b43b80-792b-57a8-95ca-f895c9ffd5aa","slug":"causes","fullItemName":"Causes"},{"id":"0d27dbd4-96a0-5e68-a500-9055328b3181","slug":"prevalence","fullItemName":"Prevalence"},{"id":"3a9601d3-ba48-59dd-ab83-85bae1310d11","slug":"complications","fullItemName":"Complications"}]},{"id":"b2a999d4-d934-55ee-beaf-8800907e0c9f","fullItemName":"Diagnosis","slug":"